{
  "benchmark_id": "pygtrie",
  "description": "Longest-prefix-match trie modelled on Google's pygtrie library: set/get/hasKey/longestPrefix/prefixes with witness-maximality-completeness specs anchored on List.isPrefixOf. Includes a prefix-chain spec family whose clean end-facts (the longest match prefix-dominates every stored match; querying the answer is a fixed point; the match set grows monotonically as the query extends) hide a structural invariant — any two stored prefixes of a common sequence are comparable, so a length-ordered pair is prefix-ordered — plus single-insertion frame/count bounds and append-distribution laws. Scope: this is the KEY-LEVEL longest-prefix-match surface — values are plain `Nat`, and the prefix APIs (`prefixes`, `longestPrefix`) return KEYS (the key-only variants), not (key, value) pairs. `get` totalizes Python's `get(key, default=None)` to `Option Nat`.",
